	$LF
	[br 
	]br
	$LF
]p
[h3 
	" Taking damage to save time
	$LF
	[a id=heading-9941 
	]a
]h3
[h4 
	" Cancelling damage animation near a wall
	$LF
	[a id=heading-9971 
	]a
]h4
[p 
	[img class=embedright src=/images/gameresources/megamanx/meggermanx3.png 
	]img
	"If you press left or right to grab a wall when X is forced toward it from being damaged, damage animation will be cancelled. Not only does this save time, but it prevents X from falling a long distance or recoiling, and thus plays a vital part in spike-shaft climbing.
	$LF
]p
[h4 
	" Touching lethal ground while damaged
	$LF
	[a id=heading-10338 
	]a
]h4
[p 
	"In many games, damage causes the player character
	$LF
	"to become invincible for a short time, even to spikes. 
	$LF
	"While by now this is nothing special, there are 
	$LF
	"situations in the Mega Man X series where using 
	$LF
	"this can save you from having to get a 
	$LF
	"weapon and backtrack to a level you already 
	$LF
	"visited in order to use it to get a Heart Tank 
	$LF
	"or Sub-Tank. You can also climb spiked shafts rapidly without using platforms if there are enemies around.
	$LF
]p
[h4 
	" Gaining height from hit recovery
	$LF
	[a id=heading-10823 
	]a
]h4
[p 
	"A rarely necessary trick, if you get hit while you are 
	$LF
	"in the air, you will very slightly ascend due to the hit 
	$LF
	"recovery animation.  Thus, you can technically gain additional 
	$LF
	"height during a jump by getting hit while you are at its peak.
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"It is possible to combine with 
	[em 
		"Cancelling damage animation near a wall
	]em
	" to cancel damage animation while still ending up on top of the wall.
	$LF
]p
[h2 
	" Bosses
	$LF
	[a id=heading-11248 
	]a
]h2
[h4 
	" Abnormal boss recoveries
	$LF
	[a id=heading-11258 
	]a
]h4
[p 
	"While in general, bosses have a one-second invincibility after being hit, there are exceptions. A concept that occurs in the X-series and not in the original is that sometimes stunning the boss with his weak weapon will make him do some different action. Occasionally, these different actions can override the current state of invincibility (either forcing on or off invincibility). It is this forcing on or off of invincibility that causes glitches. Not all tricks are glitches; some tricks simply take advantage of the programmers’ erroneous assumptions concerning invincibility.
	$LF
]p
[ul 
	[li 
		" Spark Mandrill (X1): Becomes vulnerable again while he is still frozen from Shotgun Ice.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[ul 
	[li 
		" Flame Stag (X2): Invincibility is forced off when he starts throwing flames while on the ground. Bubble Splash can force this action.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[ul 
	[li 
		" Overdrive Ostrich (X2): Becomes vulnerable again while he is still frozen from Crystal Hunter. When he breaks out of frozen animation, he is invincible for 60 frames. Just before he shoots charged Sonic Slicer, he can be hit. Then right after, invincibility is forced off and he can be hit again.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[ul 
	[li 
		" Sigma 1 (X2): Becomes vulnerable every time he performs an action from the ground. This is notable when he dashes to slash you.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[ul 
	[li 
		" Toxic Seahorse (X3): Becomes totally vulnerable (no recovery) for about 20 frames while he is still blinking from Frost Shield. Must be hit above a certain height.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[ul 
	[li 
		" Volt Catfish (X3): Invincibility is forced off to Tornado Fang when he turns blue from his super attack. Still, avoid using Tornado Fang except on the last hit.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[ul 
	[li 
		" Crush Crawfish (X3): Becomes totally vulnerable (no recovery) for about 120 frames while he is still blinking from Triad Thunder. Use a rapid-fire weapon.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[ul 
	[li 
		" Neon Tiger (X3): Invincibility is forced off when he performs his next action from the ground.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[ul 
	[li 
		" Gravity Beetle (X3): Invincibility is forced off when he is hit by Ray Splasher while flashing.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[ul 
	[li 
		" Blast Hornet (X3): Gravity Well does damage to Blast Hornet in a unique way and has nothing to do with invincibility. The blinking is for show.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[h4 
	" Defeating bosses fast to avoid long invincibility
	$LF
	[a id=heading-13362 
	]a
]h4
[ul 
	[li 
		" Wire Sponge (X2): If Wire Sponge’s health goes below 10, then after he completes his current action, he becomes invincible for a long time while using his lightning attack. If his current action is hanging on the ceiling, then you can beat him before he finishes this.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[ul 
	[li 
		" Wheel Gator (X2): Wheel Gator can be hit with Strike Chain right away at the beginning, and can be hit just before diving, thus forming a cycle.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[h4 
	" Bosses that recover like minibosses
	$LF
	[a id=heading-13835 
	]a
]h4
[p 
	"Vile (X1), Velguader (X1) (or "Sigma's Dog"), and "Sigma Virus" (X2) (the final boss), all have recovery times similar to most minibosses (around 20-30 frames recovery). For Velguader, the weapon of choice, Shotgun Ice, does not disappear on impact, but creates pellets. You want to shoot so that the pellets disappear fastest. Sigma Virus has 64 health.
	$LF
]p
[h4 
	" Sigma’s Broken Sword Defense (MMX1)
	$LF
	[a id=heading-14230 
	]a
]h4
[p 
	"Sigma uses his sword as a shield to block shots. However, if X fires Electric Spark while standing very close to the sword, the Electric Spark goes through the sword and hits him.
	$LF
]p
[h2 
	" Dialog and event script tricks
	$LF
	[a id=heading-14452 
	]a
]h2
[p 
	"A major source of dialog bugs is multiple event scripts breaking each other.
	$LF
]p
[h4 
	" Intro Skip
	$LF
	[a id=heading-14564 
	]a
]h4
[p 
	"There is a glitch where the intro scenes can be skipped.
	$LF
	"To do that (in Snes9x v1.43),
	$LF
	"press the start button exactly on the following frames, and nowhere else:
	$LF
]p
[ul 
	[li 
		" (MMX1): 358, 393, 445, 447
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" (MMX2): 441, 444, 508, 510
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" (MMX3): 441, 444, 519, 521
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[p 
	"Explanation:
	$LF
]p
[ul 
	[li 
		" The first press clears the opening as soon as possible (it is permitted to hold down any button to clear).
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" The second one skips the intro scene by glitching.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" The third button presses "Game Start" from the menu.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" The fourth button clears this menu screen without having to wait for it to fade.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[h4 
	" Vile-Zero dialog bug (MMX1)
	$LF
	[a id=heading-15142 
	]a
]h4
[p 
	"YouTube video: 
	[a class=extlink href=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Rx4DasCTb-s rel=nofollow 
		"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Rx4DasCTb-s
	]a
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"It is possible to, by delaying dialog scrolling when Zero
	$LF
	"jumps on Vile, to form a Vile/Zero mutation image.
	$LF
]p
[h4 
	" Sigma-Zero dialog bugs (MMX2)
	$LF
	[a id=heading-15344 
	]a
]h4
[p 
	"There are two versions of this glitch, both requiring
	$LF
	"the 
	[a class=extlink href=http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shoryuken rel=nofollow 
		"shōryūken
	]a
	" and all the Zero parts:
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"1) By doing a shōryūken into the center of Zero's room
	$LF
	"during the final level, you place
	$LF
	"X in the middle instead of his normal location. When Zero
	$LF
	"punches a hole in the floor, X simply falls in and the script
	$LF
	"where Sigma prepares for his first attack runs at the same
	$LF
	"time as Zero saying “Sigma lies just ahead.” This trick
	$LF
	"requires collecting all of Zero’s parts and the shōryūken.
	$LF
	"For some invincibility fun, see 
	[b 
		"Shōryūken invincibility while playing
	]b
	$LF
	"below.
	$LF
]p
[p 
	[img class=embedright src=/images/gameresources/megamanx/ZeroshootX.png 
	]img
	"2) From the rightmost point where you still maintain control of X, it is possible to dash and use shōryūken so that X ends up right between Sigma and his black Zero. From so far in, when Zero shoots at Sigma, he will hit X instead, giving him control. Then, just jump into the hole Zero makes and continue (if you are performing the invincibility trick later, use a sub-tank to refill health).
	$LF
]p
[h4 
	" 
	[a class=extlink href=http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shoryuken rel=nofollow 
		"Shōryūken
	]a
	" invincibility while playing (MMX2)
	$LF
	[a id=heading-16425 
	]a
]h4
[p 
	"There are at least 4 places in the game where the shōryūken
	$LF
	"can be used to make X invincible. The trick involves glitching
	$LF
	"an event script into executing what would be the “Gain Control of X”
	$LF
	"command while you already have control of X and are performing a
	$LF
	"shōryūken.
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"The first and most well known is during the first battle with Neo Sigma
	[a id=r1 
	]a
	[sup 
		"[
		[a href=#1 
			"1
		]a
		"]
	]sup
	".
	$LF
	"Perform the 
	[b 
		"Zero-Sigma dialog bug
	]b
	". When Sigma’s health gauge is charging,
	$LF
	"perform a shōryūken anywhere. If you are still doing it when the gauge
	$LF
	"reaches maximum, you will stop in midair and be invincible for the
	$LF
	"remainder of the battle unless you perform a shōryūken again or beat Sigma.
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"YouTube video: 
	[a class=extlink href=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LwIkwuT8ZMI#t=0m54s rel=nofollow 
		"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LwIkwuT8ZMI#t=0m54s
	]a
	$LF
]p
[p 
	[em 
		"Note: The following three tricks are not of serious interest in a speedrun. They are completely out of the way.
	]em
	[br 
	]br
	$LF
	"The others are in Morph Moth’s stage, Magna Centipede’s (without Sigma),
	$LF
	"and Bubble Crab’s. For Morph Moth’s level, simply perform a shōryūken into the battle room
	$LF
	"with the second junk robot miniboss.
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"For Magna Centipede's level, you will need a sub tank. Use shōryūken into Chop Register’s
	$LF
	"room as far as you can. You will be hit by the materializing sword and
	$LF
	"regain control. Heal up and use the shōryūken as the battle would start.
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"For Bubble Crab’s level, use the Giga Crush just as the submarine exits
	$LF
	"its bay, so that the submarine travels underneath X, who falls on it. Again, heal quickly after taking a hit and then use shōryūken. Bubble Crab’s level requires very good timing and quick reflexes to accomplish compared to the others.
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"YouTube video: 
	[a class=extlink href=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KAtozy0EItU rel=nofollow 
		"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KAtozy0EItU
	]a
	$LF
]p
[h4 
	" X’s black shots (MMX2)
	$LF
	[a id=heading-18148 
	]a
]h4
[p 
	"Whenever X is invincible from the above glitches, X will shoot black-and-orange charged X-Buster shots. This lasts until you switch weapons or X loses invincibility. Another way to gain black shots (if you didn’t get all the Zero parts) is to hit Zero last with the shōryūken.
	$LF
]p
[h4 
	" Defeat Chop Register early, but become immobile (MMX2)
	$LF
	[a id=heading-18452 
	]a
]h4
[p 
	"At Chop Register’s room, go in as far as possible without losing control of X, and use Giga Crush. If done right, the Giga Crush attack will destroy Chop Register as it barely comes on the screen. However X will be stuck (since the instruction to regain control never occurs), so this trick is not useful at all. It is also possible to use charged Remote Mine to perform this trick, since it is slow.
	$LF
]p
[h4 
	" Jump early from X-Buster upgrade demo (MMX2)
	$LF
	[a id=heading-18912 
	]a
]h4
[p 
	"After getting X-Buster upgrade in Wheel Gator’s stage, you regain control right after X stops charging and starts firing. Although you can’t walk or dash, you can jump forward (not dashing), allowing a head start. Alternatively, you can jump backward and cancel the corkscrew shot animation by grabbing the base of the capsule, but this seems to be slower.
	$LF
]p
[h4 
	" Facing backward on cut-scenes
	$LF
	[a id=heading-19318 
	]a
]h4
[p 
	"The simplest way to do this is to approach the trigger as close as possible without losing control, then press right-left (must be done from rest). In MMX1, it can be done unassisted by riding a charged Shotgun Ice platform backwards. Note that some scenes force X to look the right way.
	$LF
]p
[p 
	[img class=embedright src=/images/gameresources/megamanx/Xwrongway.png 
	]img
	$LF
]p
[h4 
	" Window of Opportunity
	$LF
	[a id=heading-19694 
	]a
]h4
[p 
	"Window of opportunity is a one-frame timeframe when you have player control (usually unintentionally). There are times in the game where this occurs:
	$LF
]p
[ul 
	[li 
		" Before all boss rematches in MMX2 which have X drop into a room (weapon switch only).
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[ul 
	[li 
		" In Crush Crawfish’s stage after you destroy the engine, just before you drop. (MMX3)
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[h4 
	" Move around before Overdrive Ostrich rematch
	$LF
	[a id=heading-20047 
	]a
]h4
[p 
	"For some reason, if you move around when you land from teleportation, Overdrive Ostrich will not begin to appear until you stand still for a frame. This trick does not seem to be useful.
	$LF
]p
[h2 
	" Other useful tricks
	$LF
	[a id=heading-20285 
	]a
]h2
[h4 
	" Flame Mammoth’s alternate path (MMX1)
	$LF
	[a id=heading-20308 
	]a
]h4
[p 
	[img class=embedright src=/images/gameresources/megamanx/glitchroom.png 
	]img
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"Using the junk heads, it is possible to enter where the heads dropped from.
	$LF
	"This glitch does not work in E version.
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"YouTube video: 
	[a class=extlink href=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MAz3t856oCk rel=nofollow 
		"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MAz3t856oCk
	]a
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"Note: This alternate path is slower, because of a
	$LF
	"mysterious climb somewhere along the way.
	$LF
]p
[h4 
	" Spike shaft no-damage hit on X (MMX1)
	$LF
	[a id=heading-20675 
	]a
]h4
[p 
	"In Boomer Kuwanger’s level, the spikes that line the walls (not the spikes underneath the barriers) do 8 damage to unarmored X. However, if X jumps off the walls (without contacting them), X gets hit but takes no damage.
	$LF
]p
[h4 
	" 
	[a class=extlink href=http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hadoken rel=nofollow 
		"Hadōken
	]a
	" sequence (MMX1)
	$LF
	[a id=heading-20938 
	]a
]h4
[p 
	[img class=embedright src=/images/gameresources/megamanx/MegaManXV1.png 
	]img
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"It is common knowledge that you must visit a certain area (near the end of Armored Armadillo’s stage, high up on the last wall with energy capsule)  five times, and you must have all the items, weapons, and upgrades to get the hadōken. However, there are a couple misconceptions:
	$LF
]p
[ul 
	[li 
		" It is assumed that you must have all the items, weapons, and upgrades to begin the sequence; this is not true. You can have nothing and start to visit the hadōken area and it will count as a visit. This is why it is sometimes reported that you need four visits (because the first visit to Armored Armadillo’s stage counts as a visit if you get close enough). As for having everything, it comes into play only on the 
		[em 
			"last
		]em
		" visit.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[ul 
	[li 
		" It is assumed that you must grab the energy capsule; this is not true. Getting near the area where the capsule would appear is enough. You can simply make X hit the lower-left corner of the visit area, as shown in the image above.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[p 
	"Note that you also need full health on the last visit to make the capsule appear.
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"The number of visits is stored in memory address 7E1F7E. Check this address to make sure that you visit.
	$LF
]p
[h4 
	" Mid-air Hadōken
	$LF
	[a id=heading-22198 
	]a
]h4
[p 
	"The mid-air hadōken can be done as follows:
	$LF
]p
[ul 
	[li 
		" Charge up Shotgun Ice and put it in a wall.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" When it forms a platform, stand on it.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Start the hadōken sequence by pressing down, down-forward, forward, then press start to enter the sub-menu.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Select X-Buster, then press fire on the first frame when you regain control.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" If done right, X will fire a hadōken in mid-air.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[p 
	"This trick is useful against Rangda Bangda (face boss) and Sting Chameleon.
	$LF
]p
[h4 
	" Bubble Crab’s Sub-Tank (MMX2)
	$LF
	[a id=heading-22667 
	]a
]h4
[p 
	"Using both 
	[em 
		"Jumping off sloped ground
	]em
	" and 
	[em 
		"Water Hopping
	]em
	" techniques,
	$LF
	"it is possible to obtain the item without charged Bubble Splash.
	$LF
